				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{FE}} = znF/Q,$$\end{document}where z is the number of electron transfer, n is the total moles of O2, F is the Faraday constant of 96485 C mol−1, and Q is the total amount of electricity.

The AQEs for CO evolution on Bi-Hx/NF were measured under the same catalytic reaction conditions with irradiation of different wavelengths (420, 450, 520, and 590 nm). The light intensity (Wl) was monitored by a PL-MW200 photoradiometer (Perfect Light, Beijing, China). Thermal contribution at 180 °C was considered in the calculation of AQEs. The radiative power of heat per unit area can be described by the Stefan–Boltzmann law53,8Q=σTr4−T04,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Q = \sigma \left( {T_{\mathrm{r}}^4 - T_0^4} \right),$$\end{document}where Tr is the reaction temperature in K and σ is Stefan–Boltzmann constant (5.67 × 10−8 W m−2 K−4). The maximal work done by the thermal energy was calculated by using the Carnot equation54,9Wh=Q1−T0/Tr,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$W_{\mathrm{h}} = Q\left( {1 - T_0/T_{\mathrm{r}}} \right),$$\end{document}where T0 is the ambient temperature for performing the CO2 reduction (299.15 K). Based on the above two equations, the real contribution of heat at 180 °C in CO2 reduction was calculated to be 65.8 mW cm−2. The AQE was calculated by:10AQE%=NumberofreactedelectronsNumberofincidentphotons×100%=NumberofevolvedCOmolecules×2Numberofincidentphotons×100%=M×NA×2W×A×t×λh×c×100%=M×NA×2Wl+Wh×A×t×λh×c×100%,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{AQE}}\;\left( \% \right) 	= \frac{{{\mathrm{Number}}\;{\mathrm{of}}\;{\mathrm{reacted}}\;{\mathrm{electrons}}}}{{{\mathrm{Number}}\;{\mathrm{of}}\;{\mathrm{incident}}\;{\mathrm{photons}}}} \times 100\% \\ 	= \frac{{{\mathrm{Number}}\;{\mathrm{of}}\;{\mathrm{evolved}}\; {\mathrm{CO}}\; {\mathrm{molecules}} {\,}\times 2}}{{{\mathrm{Number}}\;{\mathrm{of}}\;{\mathrm{incident}}\;{\mathrm{photons}}}} \times 100\% \\ 	= \frac{{M \times N_{\mathrm{A}} \times 2}}{{\frac{{W \times A \times t \times \lambda }}{{h \times c}}}} \times 100\% \\ 	= \frac{{M \times N_{\mathrm{A}} \times 2}}{{\frac{{\left( {W_l + W_h} \right) \times A \times t \times \lambda }}{{h \times c}}}} \times 100\%,$$\end{document}where M is the CO evolution rate (mol s−1), NA is Avogadro constant, W is the total energy input (W), A is irradiation area (m2), t is the time of light illumination (s), λ is the corresponding wavelength (m), h is 6.62 × 10−34 J s−1, and c is 3.0 × 108 m s−1.

To illustrate the CO2 reduction reaction activity from a thermodynamic aspect, the free energy diagrams were estimated using:11ΔG=ΔE+ΔZPE−TΔS,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\Delta}G = {\Delta}E + {\Delta}ZPE - T{\Delta}S,$$\end{document}where ΔE is the total energy change based on the DFT calculations, ZPE and S are the zero-point energy and entropy, respectively, and T is the temperature (here, 298.15 K is selected). The free energy of (H+ + e−) at standard conditions was assumed to be the energy of 1/2 H260.
